{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c7435d0a-1e23-40bf-a99f-ed59425de940","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, the iOS-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** `IgnoreSafeArea` property on `Page`.\n\n**Old (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**New (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage IgnoreSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n`IgnoreSafeArea=\"False\"` (the default) tells MAUI to respect safe area insets — keeping content clear of the status bar, Dynamic Island, and home indicator. You can remove the `xmlns:ios` namespace declaration if it was only used for `UseSafeArea`.\n\nThis now works cross-platform (iOS *and* Android), so you no longer need the platform-specific namespace for this behavior.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7ec1f22f-d63d-40fa-9450-d85b46ebb118","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` attached property was removed/deprecated. The replacement is to use `Padding` with the new `SafeAreaRegion` system, or more specifically, the new `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` property (which inverts the logic), or the new safe area padding approach.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. In .NET MAUI for .NET 10, Microsoft changed how safe areas work. \n\nThe platform-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` property is no longer available in .NET 10, replaced with a cross-platform approach that handles safe area insets differently. I think the real issue is that the iOS-specific `UseSafeArea` attribute isn't being recognized anymore in .NET 10, which is why content is appearing behind the status bar. The solution is to switch to the new cross-platform `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` property instead, setting it to `False` to ensure safe areas are respected. I'm realizing I need to be careful about the exact API name since .NET 10 is still in development. The most likely scenario is that the iOS-specific `UseSafeArea` property was generalized into a cross-platform `IgnoreSafeArea` property on the `Page` class itself, which would be set to `False` to respect safe area boundaries.","outputTokens":1459,"requestId":"142C:1837D6:2EA818:35A05A:6A03CF3C"},"id":"a2c9ac85-3cae-4d88-95c0-0e939963917f","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:09:46.772Z","parentId":"1a98ce3a-e8f7-4f31-a304-ce6a21ed0bfe"}
